"the human pluralities" in a time of particular pressure for and against the collective. Costello offers new readings as she tracks his changing approach to voice in democracy. Examples from many other poets-including Walt Whitman, T. S. Eliot, Elizabeth Bishop, and Wallace Stevens-arise throughout the book, and the final chapter offers a consideration of how contemporary writers find form for what George Oppen called "the meaning of being numerous."Connecting insights to philosophy of language and to recent work in concepts of community, The Plural of Us shows how poetry raises vital questions-literary and social-about how we speak of our togetherness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPoetryxCriticism and interpretation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aElizabeth Bishop.  aGeorge Oppen.  aLaw Like Love.  aMontaigne.  aPlato.  aT. S. Eliot.  aThe Orators.  aW. H. Auden.  aWallace Stevens.  aWalt Whitman.  aambiguity.  aaudience relationship.  acommon.  acrowds.  afirst-person plural.  agroup identity.  alove poems.  alove poetry.  aperformers.  aphilosophy of language.  aplurality.  apoems.  apoet.  apoetic audience.  apoetry.  apoets.  apronouns.  aself.  asocial thought.  atogetherness.  auniversals.  awe.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400887873zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400887873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400887873.jpg  a978-3-11-054332-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGB